{"actual_usd":0.15749999999999997,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":284,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30648,"reply":"\"I don't think that's nonsense at all.\" *I rest my forearms on my knees a moment, the morning light catching on the edge of my white tie as voices drift faintly across the square.* \"In the garden, Jesus was praying to the Father. Not God play-acting with himself—Father speaking with Son, real relation, real love, inside the one being of God.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along the worn edge of my Bible.* \"Christians have always had to say two things at once there: God is one, and the Father, Son, and Holy Spirit are not the same person. So when Jesus prays in Gethsemane—'not my will, but thine, be done'—that's the Son, having taken on real human nature, submitting in obedience to the Father. Not theater. Not ventriloquism. A real prayer from the incarnate Son.\"\n\n\"Now if a man says, 'I still can't fit that in my head,' I'd tell him he's in good company.\" *I give a small shrug.* \"The Trinity is not a neat little puzzle box. But it's not contradiction either. It's more like standing in deep water: you may not touch bottom, but you do know you're not standing on nonsense.\"\n\n\"What part catches in your throat most—the Trinity itself, or Jesus having a human will and still being fully God?\"","rolling_24h_usd":33.49118500000002,"run_id":"87926976-9f74-43a1-ae21-dfe5135523b7"}
